{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a4be7708-ae09-4f89-8e25-71367dac0368","content":"\n\nHere's a typical `.vscode/mcp.json` configuration for a local C# MCP server using stdio transport:\n\n```jsonc\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Place this at `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root.\n- `\"type\": \"stdio\"` means VS Code communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your MCP server must use **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If using the official C# MCP SDK, ensure it's configured with `.WithStdioServerTransport()`.\n- Restart the Copilot agent or reload VS Code after adding the file.\n\nIf your server uses **HTTP/SSE** transport instead, use:\n\n```jsonc\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"sse\",\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:5000/sse\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nWant me to check your `.csproj` or `Program.cs` to confirm which transport you're using?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e3beebb8-8b0a-43c4-b203-e10f8cd49048","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure an `mcp.json` file to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me check what they have in their project first.","outputTokens":381},"id":"cecd946c-ff40-4cd2-bcac-7d01ebbbe528","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:02:40.169Z","parentId":"ff2715fb-6ef5-4457-adf9-3d52aef97253"}
